The pilot stated that he was performing a water landing in a cove with gusty wind conditions. 
The airplane touched down twice and, on the third touchdown, veered violently to the left. He 
believed that he either ﬁchined and waterloopedﬂ or that the left sponson contacted the water 
first. Both sponsons and the left wing tip were substantially damaged. Additionally, the left side 
of the airplane™s nose and left fuselage at the pilot entry station were wrinkled and bent.
The pilot did not maintain directional control during a water touchdown.
